<p>With the official activation of the Ethereum Cancun upgrade, the cryptocurrency sector has reached a pivotal turning point. Widely regarded as the most influential technical innovation since The Merge, this upgrade aims to fundamentally optimize the performance and cost structure of Layer2 scaling networks by introducing core improvements like proto-danksharding. For leading Layer2 networks such as Arbitrum and Optimism, the Cancun upgrade signifies not only a significant reduction in transaction costs but also the potential to trigger a profound reshaping of DeFi, NFT ecosystems, and token value capture models. This report will provide an in-depth analysis of the specific impacts of this upgrade and assess its long-term structural changes.</p>
<h2>The Technical Core of the Cancun Upgrade: Paving the Way for Layer2</h2>
<p>The core of the Cancun upgrade is Ethereum Improvement Proposal EIP-4844, known as proto-danksharding. According to reports, this proposal introduces "blob-carrying transactions," providing dedicated space for data availability for Layer2 networks, thereby reducing the need to compete with the main chain for block space. This directly lowers the cost for Layer2 networks to submit data to the Ethereum mainnet. As announced by the Ethereum Foundation, this design aims to achieve an order-of-magnitude reduction in transaction fees. Simultaneously, the upgrade includes other optimizations, such as simplifying gas fee calculations, further enhancing network efficiency. Technically, the Cancun upgrade marks a substantive step in Ethereum''s "rollup-centric" roadmap, laying the foundation for an explosion in the Layer2 ecosystem.</p>
<h2>Specific Impact on Transaction Costs and Performance of Major Layer2 Networks</h2>
<p>The impact of the Cancun upgrade on Layer2 networks is most direct, reflected in improvements to transaction costs and throughput. The following analysis uses Arbitrum and Optimism as examples.</p>
