<p>In the NFT sector, the Cancun upgrade is expected to bring similar transformative changes. High gas fees have long been a major barrier to NFT minting and trading. Post-upgrade, the cost of NFT activities on Layer2 will decrease significantly. Industry reports suggest this could inspire more creators to launch NFTs on networks like Arbitrum and Optimism, driving diversification from art to gaming assets. Performance enhancements also support more complex NFT applications, such as dynamic NFTs and metaverse integration, thereby expanding the utility scenarios for NFTs. Long-term, the NFT ecosystem may see a large-scale migration from the Ethereum mainnet to Layer2, forming a more decentralized yet efficient creation and trading network.</p>
<h2>Reshaping Token Economics and Value Capture Models</h2>
<p>The Cancun upgrade''s impact on Layer2 token economics is crucial. Tokens represented by ARB and OP may see their value capture models shift from purely governance functions to more complex economic incentives. First, as transaction costs fall, the revenue structure of Layer2 networks may change. Reports indicate some networks are exploring fee-sharing mechanisms to return saved costs to users via token rewards. Second, the upgrade fosters ecosystem growth, allowing tokens to capture more in-application value, such as through staking for yields or participating in protocol decisions. Finally, increased competition may drive innovation in token models, such as integrating zero-knowledge proof technology to enhance privacy and efficiency, thereby reshaping investor expectations for Layer2 asset value. From a long-term structural perspective, token economics may become more tightly bound to network usage and community participation, enhancing overall sustainability.</p>
