orts indicating NVDA''s CUDA platform still dominates the developer community.</p><h3>The Role of Cloud Service Providers</h3><p>Cloud service providers like Microsoft (MSFT), Amazon''s AWS (AMZN), and Google (GOOGL) are aggressively integrating AI capabilities. Market research indicates these companies are attracting enterprise clients to the cloud by offering AI model training and inference services. For instance, Microsoft''s partnership with OpenAI is reported to have enhanced the competitiveness of its Azure cloud. Intensifying competition could lead to price wars, affecting industry profit margins, but also driving rapid technological iteration.</p><h3>Startups and the Innovation Ecosystem</h3><p>AI startup fundraising activity is frequent. According to venture capital data, funding in the AI sector has grown significantly since 2023. These companies focus on vertical applications like autonomous driving, medical diagnostics, and content generation, but their commercialization paths remain unclear. Reports indicate that some startups are overvalued, raising bubble concerns. Industry consolidation may accelerate, with large companies potentially making acquisitions to supplement technological gaps.</p><h2>Bubble Risk: Analysis of Overvaluation and Market Sentiment</h2><p>With the substantial rise in AI stocks, bubble risk has become a hot topic on Wall Street. Valuation metrics show that the Price-to-Sales (P/S) and P/E ratios of some AI-related companies have deviated from historical norms. Investment institution analysis suggests market sentiment may be overly optimistic, overlooking challenges in technology implementation and regulation. For example, media reports indicate that issues like bias and privacy in AI models are sparking regulatory discussions, which could increase compliance costs and delay product launches.</p><div class="disclaimer" style="margin-top:2em;padding:1em 1.2em;border-radius:8px;background:rgba(100,116,139,0.1);border:1px solid rgba(