 surge may depend on revolutionary technological breakthroughs. This includes: <strong>cheaper, safer, faster-charging next-generation battery technology (e.g., solid-state); the maturation and deployment of autonomous driving technology that truly liberates users and creates new business models; and more disruptive product forms and business model innovations.</strong> Tesla''s long-term bets on AI and robotics are precisely wagers on the next technological inflection point.</p><p><strong>Profit redistribution within the industry chain is likely.</strong> While profit margins in the vehicle manufacturing segment are under pressure, the value of upstream and midstream segments with technological barriers—such as advanced battery materials, semiconductors, and intelligent software/hardware—may become more pronounced.</p><h3>Conclusion</h3><p>The sharp single-day plunge in Tesla''s stock price serves as a stark market warning. It signals that the EV industry has moved beyond its wild, adolescent growth phase and is entering an adulthood that requires meticulous cultivation, testing comprehensive strength and profitability. The growth story is far from over, but the chapter has shifted from ''limitless potential'' to ''brutal survival''. For investors, a more discerning and rational lens is now required to scrutinize every player in the industry and identify those capable of forging a genuine moat amidst the trials of demand and the bloodbath of competition.</p><p><strong>Risk Disclosure:</strong> The above content is based on analysis of public market information and industry trends, provided for reference only and does not constitute any form of investment advice. The stock market carries risks; investment requires caution. The EV industry experiences rapid technological change and fierce competition. Company performance and stock prices may face significant volatility. Investors should make prudent decisions based on independent judgment.</p><div class="disclaimer" 